# Sync docs after code changes

When you finish a code change (feature, fix, refactor, CLI/output change), **before marking the task done**, check whether documentation is still accurate and update it in the same change set when needed.

## When to check

- New or changed CLI commands, flags, or output format (`bot.ps1`, `tools/play/*`)
- New or changed API endpoints or schemas (`src/lua/endpoints/*`, `openrpc.json`)
- Changed play workflow, game loop, or agent instructions
- Renamed/moved/removed files that docs link to
- Behavior changes that users or agents rely on (e.g. `estimate`, `glance`, scoring rules)

Skip doc updates only when the change is purely internal with no user/agent-visible effect.

## What to check (this repo)

| Area changed | Likely docs |
|---|---|
| Play helper / bot UX | `PLAY.md`, `tools/play/README.md` |
| Agent entry points | `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md` |
| Lua API / endpoints | `src/lua/utils/openrpc.json`, endpoint docstrings, `CLAUDE.md` |
| Architecture / setup | `docs/OVERVIEW.md`, `README.md` |
| Knowledge / rules | `knowledge/balatro/README.md`, verified JSON under `knowledge/` |

## Workflow

1. List which docs *could* be affected by your diff.
2. Open each candidate; confirm commands, examples, and described behavior still match the code.
3. Update docs in the same PR/commit when something is stale — do not leave "doc debt" for later.
4. If you intentionally skip a doc update, say why in your summary (e.g. internal refactor only).

## Examples

- Added `bot.ps1 estimate` → update `PLAY.md` command table, `tools/play/README.md`, and `bot.ps1` help text.
- Changed `estimate` output (removed header / Dusk column) → update `tools/play/README.md` and any `PLAY.md` references to old output.
- New Lua endpoint → update `openrpc.json` and endpoint list in `CLAUDE.md` / `AGENTS.md`.

Do **not** edit docs the user did not ask for when they explicitly requested code-only work — but still **check** and mention stale docs in your reply if you skip updating them.
